  author: Kim Il-son
  language: eng
  text: "My friend Kwon Ja-beom, after three years as magistrate of the county, renovated the western pavilion of the official guest house and had it made into a hall. He asked me to write a record for it. I told Ja-beom, \"Let us first give it a name, then I shall write the record. What if we call it the Hall of Obsession?\" Ja-beom asked the meaning of 'obsession.' I smiled and did not answer, and he seemed quite dissatisfied. After a long while, he dared to press me, and I said:\n\n\"Wang Shu was obsessed, and Wang Yuan too—obsessed with hidden virtue. The clever are obsessed with jealousy, the skilled with cunning. Some become obsessed with writing, others with martial prowess—obsessions born of rare talent. Some are obsessed with abstinence, others with completing their duties. The ancients named many things with this character of obsession, and yet no single obsession ever sufficed. The world is clever with words, yet you alone are obsessed, speaking without care for the resentment you kindle. The world is cunning in appearance, yet you alone are clumsy in manner, stirring hatred in others. The world is shrewd in advancement, gaining a post and fearing its loss, yet you demoted yourself from the prestigious ranks to become magistrate of a remote county—obsessed with office. The world is quick at duty, leading the people with fame foremost, serving superiors with reputation first, yet you alone sit peacefully in your study, striking down the powerful and wicked, comforting the widows and orphans, yet clumsy at collecting taxes—obsessed with governance. The lesser officials excuse their neglect, letting the official buildings decay, while the capable ones build grand structures and beautified walls, sparing no effort to gain renown. You came to the dike, repaired the crumbling buildings, neither lazy nor grandiose, employing idle hands so as not to burden the people, yet wearing yourself out—obsessed in your works.\n\nUniting all your obsessions, naming this hall after them is fitting.\" \n\nJa-beom said, \"To call me obsessed is fair, but to bring shame upon this public hall through my obsession—that cannot be right.\"\n\nI replied: \"Alas! All things between heaven and earth are governed by the Creator. Viewing them with clarity, what is not public? Yet if one clings to a single thing, nothing remains but private. If we regard them as private, then one county's holdings become but six years of private use. If we regard them as public, then one body, one family becomes but a hundred years of public trust. Even Liu Zongyuan named a stream in his care the Stream of Folly—why cannot we now call this dike's hall the Hall of Obsession? For obsession is but folly transformed; transform it again and it becomes clumsiness. The folly of Yan Hui, the folly of Gao Chai, the folly of Ning Wuzi—all were praised in the Master's school. And Zhou Maoshu's clumsiness brought clarity to the law and ended corruption. Thus naming this hall with obsession brings it not shame but glory. In gaining a magistrate of obsession, the Creator itself blesses this hall. Those the world names for cleverness and cunning, though they wish to create such a hall, could never achieve it.\"\n\nJa-beom said, \"Then I shall guard my obsession to the end of my days.\"\n\nLater I told him: \"Consider how Zi Gao refused to take shortcuts or crawl through holes, and how the Master traveled in disguise through Song. Lü Duan seemed muddled, yet in imprisoning Wang Jie'en, he did not bungle service to his lord. Sima Baikang and his brothers walked firmly on solid ground, lived without pretense their whole lives, yet they bribed a geomancer to deceive their kinfolk—they did not bungle service to their parents. The Changes prize the extraordinary, the Rites prize transformation. The ancient sages adapted to circumstances and understood flexibility. There are many such cases. You too cannot cling solely to obsession.\"\n\nJa-beom replied, \"I have grown weary of the world's cleverness and wish to guard my obsession. Yet if I follow your words, I fear I shall not reach the middle way, and my obsession will scatter.\"\n\nI laughed and said, \"You are truly obsessed.\"\n\nJa-beom opened his eyes wide but said nothing, leaned against the hall, and fell asleep."
  footnotes:
    - The 'obsession' discussed here draws on a Confucian tradition where certain forms of apparent foolishness or simplicity are actually virtues—the unwavering loyalty of Yan Hui, the honesty of Gao Chai, and the prudent adaptability of Ning Wuzi were all praised by Confucius.
    - Liu Zongyuan, a Tang dynasty official, renamed a stream near his post the 'Stream of Folly' and wrote an essay celebrating it, much as this hall is being named.
    - The tension between obsessive integrity and pragmatic flexibility reflects core concerns of Confucian and Daoist philosophy about how virtue functions in the world.
